<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1937-02-08T02:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1937-02-08T02:00:00-05:00" n="962" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d962">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">693.94244/194: Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Japan</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Grew</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to
                                the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss></hi></head>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Tokyo</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1937-02-08T16:00:00+09:00">February 8, 1937—4
                                p.m.</date><lb/>[Received February 8—7:15 a.m.]</dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>46. Department’s 25, February 6, 3 p.m. I again took up with the Vice
                            Minister for Foreign Affairs orally and informally today the question of
                            smuggling into North China, presenting the facts in general and in
                            detail. Mr. Horinouchi’s comment as formerly was that an improvement in
                            this situation may be expected when Chinese customs tariffs are reduced
                            and it is hoped that the negotiations to this end will soon be
                            resumed.</p>
                        <p>Repeated to Nanking.</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Grew</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>